    "85002908": {
      "title": "Nonlinear effects of water deficits on foliar tannin concentration",
      "abstract": "The differential effects of various levels of water deficits on carbon gain, foliage expansion, and allocation patterns were incorporated into a graphical model in an attempt to explain the inconsistent reports in the literature on the effects of water deficits on contents of phenolic compounds in plant tissues. The model predicts that the concentration of phenolic comfpounds should vary nonlinearly with water deficit. In a preliminary evaluation of this model, the foliar tannin concentration of Douglas-fir trees growing along a gradient of water availability was examined. Tannin concentration showed a strong, significant relationship with water status that was best described by a nonlinear (quadratic) equation. These results underscore the need for investigators interested in the effects of water deficits on plant secondary metabolites, or in concomitant effects on processes such as herbivory, to take quantitative measurements of water status. The model may be applicable to all classes of nonnitrogenous plant secondary metabolites, but deviations from predictions should be expected both between classes and among specific components of a class."
